def fixed_size_token_chunking(text, chunk_size=512):
    tokens = list(text)
    chunks = []

    for i in range(0, len(tokens), chunk_size):
        chunk_tokens = tokens[i:i + chunk_size]
        chunks.append("".join(chunk_tokens))
    return chunks

txt = """Open-source documentation and technical guides frequently combine concise summaries, long explanatory passages, inline examples, and multi-line code fragments into a single flowing narrative that can challenge deterministic chunking strategies. Consider a continuous paragraph that begins with a brief project overview, follows with a two-sentence description of goals and constraints, embeds a short three-line code example described inline, then moves into a long, detailed explanation of design trade-offs, includes a numbered list described within sentences, and finally closes with a cautionary note about edge cases and a pointer to related resources. When applying fixed-size token chunking, the document is sliced every N tokens regardless of meaning, which produces predictable, evenly sized chunks but can split a sentence across two chunks or sever the middle of a code example; this leads to fragmented context where retrieval may return a chunk containing the tail of an explanation without the preceding rationale, increasing the chance of misinterpretation. Fixed-size character chunking behaves similarly but is based on raw characters instead of processed tokens; it is useful when a tokenizer is unavailable or when deterministic byte-level behavior is desired, yet it shares the same weakness of bisecting semantic units—paragraphs, sentences, and code lines may be arbitrarily cut, producing chunks that are syntactically incomplete or that insert line breaks where none existed originally. Sentence-based chunking, by contrast, splits at sentence boundaries so that each chunk aligns with a natural linguistic unit; this preserves semantics better and avoids chopping code snippets or lists mid-sentence, but it can create highly variable chunk sizes and sometimes produces very short chunks that are inefficient for embedding and retrieval. In practice, a single long paragraph like this one will reveal the trade-offs: fixed-size token chunking will yield consistent retrieval latency and predictable embedding cost but may require overlap to mitigate boundary loss, which increases storage and compute; fixed-size character chunking provides a tokenizer-agnostic baseline for heterogeneous data pipelines but often necessitates downstream heuristics to reassemble semantics; sentence-based chunking offers the best immediate semantic coherence and improves relevance for short, focused queries, though it complicates batching and memory planning for models with fixed context windows. Real documents also include elements that confound simplistic approaches—inline tables described in prose, code fences that must remain intact to be useful, and lists where the meaning of one item depends heavily on the previous item—so hybrid approaches (e.g., sentence-based splitting with a token-size upper bound and optional overlap) are commonly adopted to balance coherence and efficiency. The paragraph demonstrates why deterministic rule-based chunkers remain valuable for their simplicity and speed, while also highlighting why more sophisticated, structure-aware or semantic chunking strategies are often required to maintain retrieval quality and reduce hallucination in downstream RAG systems."""

result = fixed_size_token_chunking(txt)
print(result)